{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506607"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2551"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2551"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.3,0.03,0.53,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113109"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113109"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a single episode of slurred speech that resolved after about ten minutes. There was no weakness or visual changes. He has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes and hypercholesterolaemia. His regular medications include perindopril, metformin and atorvastatin. He is an ex-smoker with a 20 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 150/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable. A CT scan excludes intracranial haemorrhage. There are no features of early ischaemia and no masses are identified. A CT angiogram reveals a 40% stenosis of the left carotid artery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clopidogrel monotherapy","Aspirin monotherapy","Intravenous thrombolysis","Dual antiplatelet therapy","Carotid endarterectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has likely experienced a transient ischaemic attack (TIA). All patients with suspected TIA require urgent antithrombotic treatment due to the high risk of stroke within seven days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual antiplatelet therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (DAPT) with aspirin plus clopidogrel is the most appropriate next step. The Australian and New Zealand Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management recommend DAPT within 24 hours of symptom onset, continuing for three weeks, followed by aspirin alone indefinitely unless contraindicated. The CHANCE and POINT trials demonstrated that initiating DAPT within 12-24 hours significantly reduces 90-day stroke risk. While DAPT does increase bleeding risk, the benefits of stroke prevention outweigh this risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin monotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient in the acute setting. While it would be appropriate after the initial three weeks of DAPT, using aspirin alone in the first three weeks would miss the opportunity for additional stroke risk reduction that DAPT provides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClopidogrel monotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be a reasonable alternative if aspirin is contraindicated, but is considered inferior to DAPT in the acute setting based on current evidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous thrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in TIA as symptoms have already resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid endarterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for carotid stenosis \u0026lt;50% as the procedural risks outweigh potential benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ABCD2 score helps stratify stroke risk in TIA patients. This patient scores 5 (age \u226560 = 1, blood pressure \u2265140/90 = 1, speech disturbance without weakness = 1, duration 10-59 minutes = 1, diabetes = 1), indicating moderate to high risk and supporting urgent DAPT initiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dual antiplatelet therapy is indicated for atheroembolic transient ischaemic attacks or minor stroke.","Carotid endarterectomy is not indicated for stenosis \u003C50%.","The ABCD2 score is used to stratify risk in patients with suspected TIA."],"references":["Hao Q, Tampi M, O\u2019Donnell M, Foroutan F, Siemieniuk R, Guyatt G. Clopidogrel plus aspirin versus aspirin alone for acute minor ischaemic stroke or high risk transient ischaemic attack: systematic review and meta-analysis. BMJ. 2018;.","Johnston S, Easton J, Farrant M, Barsan W, Conwit R, Elm J et al. Clopidogrel and Aspirin in Acute Ischemic Stroke and High-Risk TIA. New England Journal of Medicine. 2018;379(3):215-225.","Stroke and transient ischaemic attack [Internet]. eTG Complete. 2017. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Wang Y, Wang Y, Zhao X. Clopidogrel with Aspirin in Acute Minor Stroke or Transient Ischemic Attack. Journal of Vascular Surgery. 2013;58(4):1140."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"